title:
Learning Patterns from Biological Networks: A Compounded Burr
  Probability Model

sections.text:
## I. INTRODUCTION

Biological networks that follow a scale-free structure exhibit a distinctive pattern of connectivity, where a few nodes are highly interconnected (known as hubs), while the majority of nodes have relatively lower degrees of connectivity ${ }^{1-3}$. These networks provide valuable insights into the resilience and efficiency of biological systems, serving as a foundation for studying intricate biological processes ${ }^{4-7}$. Lately, there has been a surge in curiosity regarding the exploration of biological networks in real-world settings, including metabolic networks ${ }^{8-10}$, protein-protein interaction networks ${ }^{8,11-14}$, protein domain networks ${ }^{4,15}$, gene interactions ${ }^{16}$, and genetic regulatory networks ${ }^{17-19}$. These networks are considered real-world complex systems and have been predominantly modeled using graph theory ${ }^{20,21}$. Metabolic networks have been extensively studied, providing insights into the interconnected biochemical reactions that drive cellular processes ${ }^{8-10}$. Protein-protein interaction networks have been explored, shedding light on the physical interactions between proteins and their functional implications ${ }^{8,11-14}$. Protein domain networks have been investigated, revealing the modular organization of proteins and their functional domains ${ }^{4,15}$. Gene interactions and genetic regulatory networks have been analyzed, elucidating the complex regulatory mechanisms that govern gene expression and cellular processes ${ }^{16-19}$.

Biological networks provide a valuable framework for modeling the structure of biological systems ${ }^{22-24}$. In these networks, nodes represent biological elements, and edges connect elements that interact with each other ${ }^{25-27}$. The number

of edges connected to each node, known as its node degree, is categorized as in-degree for incoming edges and out-degree for outgoing edges. Studying the distribution of node degrees is essential for understanding the connectivity patterns within a network and identifying hubs-nodes with a high number of connections ${ }^{28}$. Degree distribution indicates whether the network has a homogeneous or heterogeneous structure in terms of node connectivity. Understanding these structural patterns is essential for modeling how networks evolve over time, grow or shrink, and how new nodes and edges are likely to form. By utilizing graph theory and analyzing the degree distribution, researchers gain a deeper understanding of the functional and structural characteristics of complex biological systems ${ }^{1,29,30}$. Modeling biological systems through biological networks offers a powerful approach to studying the intricate interactions and behaviors within these systems, ultimately contributing to a deeper understanding of the underlying mechanisms ${ }^{1,29}$. Cutting-edge advancements in deep learning techniques have provided a formidable approach to deciphering intricate patterns and extracting valuable insights from intricate biological networks ${ }^{31-35}$.

Standard existing distributions like power law, exponential, log-normal, Poisson, etc., have been widely used to model degree distributions in different types of networks. However, these distributions may not always accurately capture the intricacies and nuances of real-world complex networks, which often exhibit heterogeneity, assortativity, and other complex patterns. Khanin and $\mathrm{Wit}^{6}$ highlighted that gene interaction networks determined by synthetic lethal interactions ${ }^{16}$, metabolic interaction networks ${ }^{16}$, and protein-protein interaction networks ${ }^{12,36}$ do not follow a power-law distribution, although some of these networks may exhibit a truncated power-law distribution. Clauset et al. ${ }^{37}$ analyzed various realworld datasets and demonstrated that while some datasets supported the power-law claim, others did not, using maximumlikelihood estimation and statistical tests for goodness-of-fit, utilizing Kolmogorov-Smirnov statistic and likelihood ratios. Salem ${ }^{38}$ discussed the impact of disturbances in biological networks on disease susceptibility in living cells. A study by Goldstein and Morris ${ }^{39}$ highlighted the importance of evaluating the goodness-of-fit of the distribution and discovered that the power-law distribution is not an adequate fit for certain cases. On the other hand, Clauset et al. ${ }^{37}$ demonstrated various parameter estimation methods and concluded that while the power-law distribution fits some datasets well, it fails to represent other datasets accurately. Broido and Clauset ${ }^{2}$ argued that strictly scale-free networks are rare and introduced notions of weak or strong scale-free networks. Voitalov et al. ${ }^{40}$ demonstrated a close relationship between the scale-free property and the Pareto type-II or Lomax distribution. Some recent studies have demonstrated the use of Lomax ${ }^{41}$, Burr ${ }^{42}$, and other heavy-tailed distributions ${ }^{43}$ for modeling real-world complex networks. Broido and Clauset ${ }^{2}$ further noted that recent complex network datasets deviate from the power-law distribution, supporting earlier claims by ${ }^{44}$. In 2020, Clote ${ }^{50}$ presented an efficient algorithm for computing the connectivity density function of homopolymer secondary structures, addressing the computational challenges posed by the expo-
nential size of such networks. The obtained hypothesis tests strongly indicated that homopolymer RNA secondary structure networks are not scale-free. Introducing a new degree distribution allows us to provide a better fit to empirical data, thereby improving the accuracy of network analysis models. Additionally, a novel distribution may uncover important hidden patterns or phenomena within networks. It can also critically evaluate existing assumptions about network structure and behavior. Therefore, by exploring different parameterizations and characteristics of the new distribution, we can reveal hidden aspects of network organization and behavior that were not apparent through the existing models. This can lead to new theoretical discoveries and practical applications across various disciplines, from sociology and biology to computer science and economics. Hence, introducing a new degree distribution enhances the robustness and reliability of network analysis methods, facilitating more accurate predictions and insights into real-world systems.

Many real-world complex networks, including biological networks, do not strictly adhere to power-law distributions; instead, they may exhibit characteristics such as truncated tails, multimodality, or deviations from pure scale-free behavior. In such cases, the Burr distribution can provide a better empirical fit, allowing us to model network data more accurately and extract more reliable insights into network structure and behavior ${ }^{45}$. The Burr distribution is highly flexible and versatile, capable of modeling a wide range of shapes and heavytail behaviors. Due to its flexibility, it might be able to fit network degree distributions with different levels of heterogeneity and heavy tails that are common in biological networks. The Burr distribution has well-defined statistical properties, including moments, cumulative distribution function, and tail behavior indices (e.g., shape parameters), which are essential for quantitative analysis in network science. These properties may allow us to derive meaningful interpretations about network characteristics such as centralization, assortativity, and resilience based on the distribution of node degrees. This paper introduces a novel family of distributions with the Burr degree distribution as the baseline. Recently, Burr distribution with nonlinear exponent ${ }^{43}$, Marhsall-Olkin generalization of Burr (Burr $\mathrm{MO}^{46}$ ), and exponentiated Burr distribution ${ }^{47}$ have shown excellent performance to better fit the large-scale heavy-tailed networks better than the popularly used power law and other probability models. However, for a few cases, it cannot cover the entire distribution pattern of complex largescale networks ${ }^{42}$. Thus, a modification or a more accurate modelling of the degree distribution is required. The proposed Compounded Burr (CBurr) distribution is a member of a specific family of continuous probability distributions, which introduces a new way of incorporating a parameter to expand the Burr XII distribution. The proposed distribution aims to improve the fitting of biological network data across the entire range, outperforming commonly used power-law distributions such as Pareto, Lomax, Burr distributions, and some other distributions in most biological networks.

Our proposal increases the flexibility of the model, allowing it to better capture the nuances of the degree distributions in complex networks, particularly when the network exhibits

a mixture of different subpopulations with varying connectivity patterns. Real-world complex networks, such as social networks, biological networks, and technological networks, often show multi-scale behavior in their degree distributions and, hence, do not conform perfectly to a single distribution form ${ }^{48}$. Thus, the compounded Burr distribution, by blending two distributions, can provide a better fit and is well-suited to capture these behaviors, as it can model both the heavy-tailed nature of the distribution and the varying scales of connectivity present within different parts of the network. Therefore, it may lead to a more accurate modeling of the network's structure, which is crucial for understanding its dynamics and resilience. We have demonstrated the general properties of this new distribution family, including maximum likelihood estimation. Furthermore, the proposed CBurr distribution model is applied to comprehensively analyze large-scale biological network data. This analysis aims to demonstrate the effectiveness of the proposed distribution in capturing the intricate connectivity and behavior exhibited by biological networks, surpassing the limitations of power-law models. In essence, the proposed model enables effective modeling of the degree distribution of complex biological networks across the entire range of data, eliminating the need to discard lowerdegree nodes. The practical application of this novel distribution family is demonstrated using large-scale heavy-tailed biological network datasets surpassing the performance of commonly utilized heavy-tailed distributions. Overall, the proposed CBurr distribution for modeling the degree distribution of biological networks aims to represent network connectivity accurately, improve biological interpretation, network analysis, and prediction, and develop new statistical models.

The structure of the remaining paper is as follows: Section II discusses a motivating example from biological networks, and Section III presents the genesis of the proposed family of distribution and its statistical properties to provide a better understanding of the proposed model. Section IV introduces the Compounded Burr (CBurr) distribution, including its statistical properties such as parameter estimation. In Section V, we present experimental results and analyze them in the context of various real-world complex networks. Finally, Section VI concludes the paper with a concise summary and discussion.

## II. MOTIVATING EXAMPLES

One of the key structural features in analyzing real-world complex networks is the degree distribution. Degree distribution of nodes, especially a power-law degree distribution, has been regarded as one of the most significant structural characteristics of social, information, and biological networks. Empirical studies on real-world network patterns suggest that their degree distributions follow a single power-law, often called a scale-free network. The main reason behind the emergence of this phenomenon is the mechanism of preferential attachment, which states that in a growing network, a node with a higher degree is more likely to receive new links. In 1999, Barabási ${ }^{1}$ modeled the degree distribution of the World Wide Web (WWW) using a single power-law. Since then, this struc-
tural pattern has been extensively studied across various realworld networks, including metabolic, gene regulatory, collaboration, communication, and social networks. These networks are inherently dynamic, as their vertices and/or edges continue to grow over time. This dynamic nature can be effectively captured by studying the underlying pattern of node degree distribution.

However, upon closer examination of the entire network data, this single power-law distribution often fails to represent the data accurately because of the presence of large fluctuations and sparsity in the upper and lower tails of the degree distribution. If the degree distribution followed a single power law, then a single straight line would be enough to fit all the data points completely when viewed on the loglog scale. However, Fig. 1 (right) clearly demonstrates that this is not the case. We analyzed a bio-Dmela heavy-tailed network ${ }^{49}$ and visualized the node degree distribution on both the original scale and the log-log scale (see Fig. 1). When attempting to fit a single power-law model to the entire bioDmela network data, we observed that the blue straight line (see Fig. 1 (right)) representing the power-law fit failed to align with many data points, particularly those corresponding to lower-degree nodes, indicating a poor fit in those regions. This suggests that when modeling with a single power law, greater emphasis is placed on higher-degree nodes, while many lower-degree nodes, potentially containing valuable information about the network, are overlooked or disregarded. Finally, our observation from Fig. 1 (right) reveals that the node degree distribution of the bio-Dmela network, when plotted on a log-log scale, exhibits nonlinearity (as shown by the yellow curve in Fig. 1 (right)) upon closer inspection. This behavior differs from the pattern observed when a single power-law model is applied and has also been noted in many other biological networks. Therefore, when fitting the degree distribution, it is crucial to consider all nodes, including both lower-degree and higher-degree nodes, to accurately capture the true pattern of the network's degree distribution. This is why more research is being done to find a model that can accurately describe the main features of heavy-tailed and longtailed behavior in the entire degree distribution of real-world complex networks. This article contributes to that effort by introducing a novel heavy-tailed compounded Burr distribution, a variant of the widely used heavy-tailed Burr distribution for effectively capturing the structural characteristic of the node degree distribution of real world networks.

## III. MODEL FORMULATION

As a practical example, we consider a complex biological network, such as a protein-protein interaction network, which consists of various interacting proteins. In this example, the network undergoes dynamic processes, and we want to investigate the time it takes for a specific protein to be activated or inhibited, denoted as the activation/inhibition time. Each vertex in the network represents a specific entity, such as a protein in a protein-protein interaction network. The activation/inhibition time for a specific protein (vertex) is defined

FIG. 1: Plots of the node degree distribution of bio-Dmela network in the Original scale (left) and in the Log-Log scale (right). It is clear from the plot (right) that power law distribution does not provide a 'good' fitting for the bio-Dmela data, and there is a need for heavy-tailed probability distribution to provide a 'good' nonlinear fitting.
as the minimum value among the random variables $X_{i}$, which represents the time intervals between these events. Assuming that the activation/inhibition events are stochastic occurrences that can happen multiple times in the network's dynamics, we model the time interval between each event using independent and identically distributed random variables $X_{i}$, where $i=1,2, \cdots, N$ and $(N-1)$ is a Poisson random variable with parameter $0 \leq \lambda \leq \infty^{50,51}$. The continuous probability distribution function for these random variables is represented as $F(\cdot)$. Therefore, the activation/inhibition time for the specific protein of interest is defined as the minimum value among these random variables:

$$
Y=\min \left\{X_{1}, X_{2}, \cdots, X_{N}\right\}
$$

Here, $Y$ represents the activation/inhibition time for the specific protein of interest, and $N$ is the number of such events (activation/inhibition events). Let us assume that $N-1$ is independent of the random variables $X_{i}$ and follows a Poisson distribution with parameter $\lambda$, where $0 \leq \lambda<\infty$. In this scenario, we can determine the probability mass function of the number of activation or inhibition events, denoted as $N-1$, which is given by:

$$
P(N-1=n-1)=\frac{e^{-\lambda} \lambda^{n-1}}{(n-1)!}, n=1,2, \ldots
$$

where the parameter $\lambda$ determines the expected number of these activation or inhibition events occurrences over a specified period. Further, the survival function of the minimum activation/inhibition time, denoted as $Y$, can be calculated as

$$
\begin{aligned}
\bar{G}(y) & =P\left[X_{1} \geq y, X_{2} \geq y, \ldots, X_{n} \geq y\right]:=P(Y \geqslant y) \\
& =\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} P[Y \geq y \mid N-1=n-1] P[N-1=n-1] \\
& =\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}[\bar{F}(y)]^{n} \frac{e^{-\lambda} \lambda^{n-1}}{(n-1)!}=\frac{\bar{F}(y)}{\exp \{\lambda F(y)\}}
\end{aligned}
$$

where $\bar{F}(y)$ represents the survival function of $X$. It is worth noting that the ratio $\bar{F}(y) / \bar{G}(y)$ is non-decreasing for $y \geqslant 0$, shown as

$$
\frac{\bar{F}(y)}{\bar{G}(y)}=\exp \{\lambda F(y)\}
$$

The associated PDF of $Y$ is expressed as:

$$
g(y ; \lambda)=\frac{f(y)[1+\lambda \bar{F}(y)]}{\exp \{\lambda F(y)\}}, \quad-\infty<y<\infty, 0 \leqslant \lambda<\infty
$$

Using the same arguments as discussed above, we can calculate the maximum activation/inhibition time, which can be defined as

$$
Z=\max \left\{X_{1}, X_{2}, \cdots, X_{N}\right\}
$$

The distribution function of the maximum activation/inhibition time, denoted as $Z$, can be obtained as

$$
G(z):=P(Z \leqslant z)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}[F(z)]^{n} \frac{e^{-\lambda} \lambda^{n-1}}{(n-1)!}=\frac{F(z)}{\exp \{\lambda \bar{F}(z)\}}
$$

where $\bar{F}(z)$ represents the survival function of $X$. The associated probability density function (PDF) of $Z$, denoted as $g(z ; \lambda)$, is given by:

$$
g(z ; \lambda)=\frac{f(z)[1+\lambda F(z)]}{\exp \{\lambda \bar{F}(z)\}}, \quad-\infty<z<\infty, 0 \leqslant \lambda<\infty
$$

This method acts as a skewing mechanism, as illustrated by the following theorem:

Theorem 1 If the original distribution $F$ of $X$ is symmetric, then the distribution of $-Y$ is equivalent to the distribution of $Z$.

## Proof 1

$$
g(-y ; \lambda)=\frac{f(y)[1+\lambda F(y)]}{\exp \{\lambda \bar{F}(y)\}}, \quad-\infty<y<\infty, 0 \leq \lambda<\infty
$$

It is evident that the PDFs in (3) and (4) of $Y$ and $Z$ can be expressed as weighted versions of any random variable using the following weight functions:

$$
w(y ; \lambda)=\frac{1+\lambda \bar{F}(y)}{\exp \{\lambda F(y)\}} \text { and } w(z ; \lambda)=\frac{1+\lambda F(z)}{\exp \{\lambda \bar{F}(z)\}}
$$

The weight functions $w(y ; \lambda)$ and $w(z ; \lambda)$ exhibit different monotonicity properties. Specifically, $w(y ; \lambda)$ is a nonincreasing function, while $w(z ; \lambda)$ is a non-decreasing function, for $\lambda \geq 0$. Consequently, if the base random variable ( $R V$ ) $X$ has a decreasing PDF, then $Y$ also has a decreasing PDF. Additionally, in the case where $X$ follows an unimodal PDF, it can be observed that the mode of $Y$ is less than the mode of $X$ for $\lambda>0$.

The following theorem demonstrates that the proposed method results in a generalization of the base distribution, preserving the same moment existence properties as the original distribution for any general $F$. This theorem establishes that the newly derived distribution retains the moment characteristics of the underlying distribution, ensuring consistency in terms of moment existence.

Theorem 2 The moments of $G$ exist in the same order as in the original distribution $F$.

## Proof 2

g(y ; \lambda)=w(y ; \lambda) f(y)
$$

where $w(y ; \lambda)$ takes values between $(1 / e, 1)$ when $0<\lambda<1$ and $(0,1)$ if $\lambda>1$. The result follows.

Remark 1 Also, note that if the method is applied twice, another new family turns up, viz.,

\bar{H}(y)=\frac{\bar{F}(y)}{\exp \{\lambda[F(y)+G(y)]\}}
$$

## A. Hazard rates and risk functions

In the context of reliability and survival data analysis, we introduce a transformation to the distribution $G(y: \lambda)$, which incorporates a new parameter $\lambda \geq 0$ into any existing family of
continuous distributions. This transformation is defined based on the survival function of the distribution given:

$$
\bar{G}(y)=\frac{\bar{F}(y)}{\exp \{\lambda F(y)\}}
$$

By assuming the continuity of $F$ throughout, we can derive the corresponding density function as follows:

$$
g(y ; \lambda)=\frac{f(y)[1+\lambda \bar{F}(y)]}{\exp \{\lambda F(y)\}}, \quad-\infty<y<\infty, 0 \leq \lambda<\infty
$$

The parameter $\lambda$ can be interpreted in terms of the ratio of the hazard rates between $G$ and $F$, as expressed by the following equation:

$$
\frac{r_{G}(y)}{r_{F}(y)}=1+\lambda \bar{F}(y)
$$

Notably, $G$ encompasses a broader class of distributions compared to the original distribution $F$; we name it compounded family of distributions. The hazard ratio, denoted as $[1+\lambda \bar{F}(y)]$, indicates that the model follows a proportional hazard-based representation similar to the Cox proportional hazard model ${ }^{52}$. Note that, $\lim _{y \rightarrow-\infty} r_{G}(y ; \lambda)=\lim _{y \rightarrow-\infty}(1+$ $\lambda) r_{F}(y)$ and $\lim _{y \rightarrow \infty} r_{G}(y ; \lambda)=\lim _{y \rightarrow \infty} r_{F}(y)$. The following theorem establishes limits on the hazard rate function and the survival function.

Theorem 3 For all $\lambda>0$,
(i) $r_{F}(y) \leqslant r_{G}(y ; \lambda) \leqslant(1+\lambda) r_{F}(y)$;
(ii) $\bar{F}^{1+\lambda}(y) \leqslant \bar{G}(y ; \lambda) \leqslant \bar{F}(y)$.

Proof 3 From (7), we can easily verify that for $\lambda>0$, $r_{G}(y ; \lambda) \geqslant r_{F}(y)$. Again, one can see that for $\lambda>0$,

$$
\begin{aligned}
r_{G}(y ; \lambda)-(1+\lambda) r_{F}(y) & =(1+\lambda \bar{F}(y)) r_{F}(y)-(1+\lambda) r_{F}(y) \\
& =-\lambda F(y) r_{F}(y) \leqslant 0
\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, the result (i) is deduced, and by utilizing the result (i), we can establish the validity of the result (ii).

The subsequent theorem provides valuable insights into the concepts of excess risk (the rate of disease in an exposed population divided by the rate of disease in an unexposed population) and relative risk (a ratio of the probability of an event occurring in the exposed group versus the probability of the event occurring in the non-exposed group), which will be of interest in epidemiology and medical science.
Theorem 4 For all $\lambda>0$,

$$
0 \leqslant G(y)-F(y) \leqslant e^{\lambda}-1 \text { and } \frac{\bar{G}(y)}{\bar{F}(y)} \text { is decreasing in } y
$$

Proof 4 From Eq. (2), it follows that for $\lambda>0, \bar{G}(y) \leqslant \bar{F}(y)$. Furthermore, it is evident that for values of $\lambda$ greater than zero,

$$
G(y)-F(y) \leqslant[\exp \{\lambda F(y)\}-1] \bar{F}(y) \leqslant e^{\lambda}-1
$$

Hence, for $\lambda>0,0 \leqslant G(y)-F(y) \leqslant e^{\lambda}-1$.
Moreover, $\frac{\bar{G}(y)}{\bar{F}(y)}=\exp \{-\lambda F(y)\}$ is decreasing in $y$ for $\lambda>0$.

Thus, relative risk provides an increase or decrease in the likelihood of an event based on some exposure and is an important consideration in biological and medical science.

## B. Moments

In probability and statistics, moments are popularly used to describe the characteristics of a distribution. For the compounded family of distributions, we can find closed-form expressions of moments derived below. The density function of $Y$ given in (3) can be written as

$$
g(y ; \lambda)=[1+\lambda \bar{F}(y)] e^{-\lambda F(y)} f(y),-\infty<y<\infty, 0 \leq \lambda<\infty
$$

Now, for $\lambda>0$, Eq. (8) can be expressed as

$$
\begin{aligned}
g(y ; \lambda)= & f(y)[1+\lambda \bar{F}(y)] \sum_{j=0}^{\infty} \frac{(\lambda \bar{F}(y)-\lambda)^{j}}{j!} \\
= & f(y)\left[\sum_{j=0}^{\infty} \sum_{k=0}^{j} \frac{1}{j!}\binom{j}{k}(-1)^{j-k} \lambda^{j} \bar{F}^{k}(y)+\right. \\
& \left.\sum_{j=0}^{\infty} \sum_{k=0}^{j} \frac{1}{j!}\binom{j}{k}(-1)^{j-k} \lambda^{j+1} \bar{F}^{k+1}(y)\right] \\
= & f(y)\left[\sum_{j=0}^{\infty} \sum_{k=0}^{j} a_{j, k} \bar{F}^{k}(y)+\sum_{j=0}^{\infty} \sum_{k=0}^{j} \lambda a_{j, k} \bar{F}^{k+1}(y)\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

where $a_{j, k}=\frac{1}{j!}\binom{j}{k}(-1)^{j-k} \lambda^{j}$. Probability weighted moments (PWMs), proposed by Greenwood et al. ${ }^{53}$, are statistical measures that represent expectations of certain functions of a random variable when its mean exists. If we express the probability-weighted moments in terms of the density function $f(y)$, then the corresponding equation is given by

$$
M_{p, r, s}=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty} x^{p}(F(x))^{r}(1-F(x))^{s} f(x) d x
$$

where $p, r$, and $s$ are positive integers. Note that the moments $M_{p, 0,0}$ are the noncentral conventional moments. The PWMs for the baseline survival function $\bar{F}(y)$ are defined by

$$
M_{p, 0, s}=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty} x^{p}(\bar{F}(x))^{s} f(x) d x
$$

Hence, from Eq. (9), the $r$-th moment of $Y$ for $\lambda>0$ can be written as

$$
\begin{aligned}
E\left(Y^{r}\right)= & \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} y^{r} g(y) d y \\
= & \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} \sum_{j=0}^{\infty} \sum_{k=0}^{j} a_{j, k} y^{r} \bar{F}^{k}(y) f(y) d y+ \\
& \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} \sum_{j=0 k=0}^{\infty} \sum_{k=0}^{j} \lambda a_{j, k} y^{r} \bar{F}^{k+1}(y) f(y) d y \\
= & \sum_{j=0}^{\infty} \sum_{k=0}^{j} a_{j, k} \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} y^{r} \bar{F}^{k}(y) f(y) d y+ \\
= & \sum_{j=0}^{\infty} \sum_{k=0}^{j} a_{j, k} M_{r, 0, k}+\lambda \sum_{j=0}^{\infty} \sum_{k=0}^{j} a_{j, k} M_{r, 0, k+1}
\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, we can see a closed form for the moments of the proposed family of distribution. The following result shows that the mean residual life function of the random variable $Y$ can be represented by PWMs of the residual random variable $X_{t}=(X-t \mid X>t)$.
Theorem 5 The mean residual, given the survival to $t$ until the protein-protein interaction network experiences its first damaging event of the compounded family of distribution, can be obtained as follows, following ${ }^{51}$ :

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mu_{G}(t) & =E(Y-t \mid Y>t) \\
& =e^{\lambda F(t)} \sum_{j=0}^{\infty} \sum_{k=0}^{j} a_{j, k}\left[M_{1,0, k}(t)+\lambda M_{1,0, k+1}(t)\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

Proof 5 Suppose that $Y_{t}=(Y-t \mid Y>t)$ be the residual life of the system at age $t$ with density function $g(y+t) / \bar{G}(t)$, for $\bar{G}(t)>0$. Then for $\lambda>0$, the mean residual lifetime of the random variable $Y$ is given by

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mu_{G}(t)= & \frac{1}{\bar{G}(t)} \int_{0}^{\infty} y g(y+t) d y \\
= & \frac{1}{\bar{G}(t)} \int_{0}^{\infty} y f(y+t)\left[\sum_{j=0 k=0}^{\infty} \sum_{k=0}^{j} a_{j, k}(\bar{F}(y+t))^{k}+\right. \\
& \left.\sum_{j=0 k=0}^{\infty} \sum_{k=0}^{j} \lambda a_{j, k}(\bar{F}(y+t))^{k+1}\right] d y \\
= & \frac{e^{\lambda F(t)}}{\bar{F}(t)} \sum_{j=0}^{\infty} \sum_{k=0}^{j}\left[\int_{0}^{\infty} y(\bar{F}(y+t))^{k} f(y+t) d y+\right. \\
& \left.\quad \lambda \int_{0}^{\infty} y(\bar{F}(y+t))^{k+1} f(y+t) d y\right] \\
= & e^{\lambda F(t)} \sum_{j=0}^{\infty} \sum_{k=0}^{j}\left[M_{1,0, k}(t)+\lambda M_{1,0, k+1}(t)\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

where, $M_{1,0, k}(t)=\frac{1}{\bar{F}(t)} \int_{0}^{\infty} y(\bar{F}(y+t))^{k} f(y+t) d y$.
The mean residual life function $\mu_{G}(t)$ at age $t$ is defined to be the expected remaining life given survival to age $t$; it is a function of interest in actuarial studies, survival analysis, and reliability.

## IV. PROPOSED CBURR DISTRIBUTION

Irving W. Burr introduced 12 distinct cumulative distribution functions, which have been valuable for data analysis ${ }^{45}$. Among these functions, the Burr XII distribution (commonly known as the Burr distribution) has garnered significant attention in the past decade due to its ability to generate a broad range of skewness and kurtosis values ${ }^{54}$. The Burr distribution is particularly well-suited for analyzing heavy-tailed network data, surpassing distributions such as Exponential, Gamma, and Weibull.

## A. Definition and Statistical Properties

The cumulative distribution function (CDF) and PDF of the Burr distribution are mathematically formulated as given below ${ }^{55}$.
Definition 1 Let $X$ be a random variable following the Burr distribution with parameters $\alpha, \gamma$, and $c$. The cumulative distribution function (CDF) of $X$ can be expressed as:

$$
F(y ; \alpha, \gamma, c)=1-\left[1+\left(\frac{y}{\gamma}\right)^{c}\right]^{-\alpha}, y>0, \alpha, \gamma, c>0
$$

where, $\gamma$ represents the scale parameter, and $\alpha$ and $c$ are shape parameters. The probability density function (PDF) of the Burr distribution is given by:

$$
f(y ; \alpha, \gamma, c)=c \alpha \gamma^{c} y^{c-1}\left[1+\left(\frac{y}{\gamma}\right)^{c}\right]^{-\alpha-1}, y>0, \alpha, \gamma, c>0
$$

The survival function corresponding to the Burr distribution can be defined as follows:

$$
\bar{F}(y ; \alpha, \gamma, c)=\left[1+\left(\frac{y}{\gamma}\right)^{c}\right]^{-\alpha}, y>0, \alpha, \gamma, c>0
$$

The hazard rate function associated with the Burr distribution can be expressed as:

$$
h(y ; \alpha, \gamma, c)=c \alpha \gamma^{c} y^{c-1}\left[1+\left(\frac{y}{\gamma}\right)^{c}\right]^{-1}, y>0, \alpha, \gamma, c>0
$$

In the specific case where the random variables $X_{i}$ follow the Burr distribution with the distribution function given in Eq. (11), the proposed compounded family of distribution in Eq. (1) can be written as:

$$
\bar{G}(y)=e^{-\lambda}\left[1+\left(\frac{y}{\gamma}\right)^{c}\right]^{-\alpha} e^{\lambda\left(1+\left(\frac{y}{\gamma}\right)^{c}\right)^{-\alpha}}
$$

The associated PDF for CBurr distribution is given by:

$$
g(y)=\frac{c \alpha y^{c-1} e^{-\lambda} e^{\lambda\left(1+\left(\frac{y}{\gamma}\right)^{c}\right)^{-\alpha}}}{\gamma^{c}\left[1+\left(\frac{y}{\gamma}\right)^{c}\right]^{\alpha+1}}\left[1+\frac{\lambda}{\left(1+\left(\frac{y}{\gamma}\right)^{c}\right)^{\alpha}}\right]
$$

and the corresponding hazard rate function is given by:

$$
r_{G}(y)=\frac{c \alpha \gamma^{c} y^{c-1}}{1+\left(\frac{y}{\gamma}\right)^{c}}\left[1+\frac{\lambda}{\left(1+\left(\frac{y}{\gamma}\right)^{c}\right)^{\alpha}}\right]
$$

By utilizing Eq. (9), we can express the density function as follows:

$$
\begin{aligned}
g(y ; \lambda)= & c \alpha \gamma^{-c} y^{c-1}\left(1+\left(\frac{y}{\gamma}\right)^{c}\right)^{-\alpha-1} \\
& {\left[\sum_{j=0}^{\infty} \sum_{k=0}^{j} a_{j, k}\left(1+\left(\frac{y}{\gamma}\right)^{c}\right)^{-k \alpha}+\right.} \\
& \left.\lambda \sum_{j=0}^{\infty} \sum_{k=0}^{j} a_{j, k}\left(1+\left(\frac{y}{\gamma}\right)^{c}\right)^{-(k+1) \alpha}\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

where $a_{j, k}=\frac{1}{j!}\binom{j}{k}(-1)^{j-k} \lambda^{j}$. By examining Eq. (10), it is evident that

$$
E\left(Y^{r}\right)=\sum_{j=0}^{\infty} \sum_{k=0}^{j} a_{j, k} M_{r, 0, k}+\lambda \sum_{j=0}^{\infty} \sum_{k=0}^{j} a_{j, k} M_{r, 0, k+1}
$$

where
$M_{r, 0, k}=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty} y^{r} \bar{F}^{k}(y) f(y) d y=\alpha \gamma^{r} \frac{\Gamma\left(\alpha(k+1)-\frac{r}{c}\right) \Gamma\left(\frac{r}{c}+1\right)}{\Gamma(\alpha(k+1)+1)}$,
and

$$
M_{r, 0, k+1}=\alpha \gamma^{r} \frac{\Gamma\left(\alpha(k+2)-\frac{r}{c}\right) \Gamma\left(\frac{r}{c}+1\right)}{\Gamma(\alpha(k+2)+1)}
$$

Therefore, the $r^{\text {th }}$ moment of the random variable $Y$ can be expressed as

$$
\begin{aligned}
E\left(Y^{r}\right)=\alpha \gamma^{r} \Gamma\left(\frac{r}{c}\right. & +1) {\left[\sum_{j=0}^{\infty} \sum_{k=0}^{j} a_{j, k} \frac{\Gamma\left(\alpha(k+1)-\frac{r}{c}\right)}{\Gamma(\alpha(k+1)+1)}\right.} \\
& \left.+\lambda \sum_{j=0}^{\infty} \sum_{k=0}^{j} a_{j, k} \frac{\Gamma\left(\alpha(k+2)-\frac{r}{c}\right)}{\Gamma(\alpha(k+2)+1)}\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

In particular, we have these two equations for the mean calculation and $2^{\text {nd }}$ order moment (relevant for the variance of the proposed CBurr distribution.

$$
\begin{aligned}
E(Y)=\alpha \gamma \Gamma\left(\frac{1}{c}\right. & +1) {\left[\sum_{j=0}^{\infty} \sum_{k=0}^{j} a_{j, k} \frac{\Gamma\left(\alpha(k+1)-\frac{1}{c}\right)}{\Gamma(\alpha(k+1)+1)}\right.} \\
& \left.+\lambda \sum_{j=0}^{\infty} \sum_{k=0}^{j} a_{j, k} \frac{\Gamma\left(\alpha(k+2)-\frac{1}{c}\right)}{\Gamma(\alpha(k+2)+1)}\right] \\
E\left(Y^{2}\right)=\alpha \gamma^{2} \Gamma\left(\frac{2}{c}\right. & +1) {\left[\sum_{j=0}^{\infty} \sum_{k=0}^{j} a_{j, k} \frac{\Gamma\left(\alpha(k+1)-\frac{2}{c}\right)}{\Gamma(\alpha(k+1)+1)}+\right.} \\
& \left.\lambda \sum_{j=0}^{\infty} \sum_{k=0}^{j} a_{j, k} \frac{\Gamma\left(\alpha(k+2)-\frac{2}{c}\right)}{\Gamma(\alpha(k+2)+1)}\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

In the case where the baseline distribution function follows the Burr distribution, the mean residual life function of the random variable $Y$ can be represented as

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mu_{G}(t) & =E(Y-t \mid Y>t) \\
& =e^{\lambda F(t)} \sum_{j=0}^{\infty} \sum_{k=0}^{j} a_{j, k}\left[M_{1,0, k}(t)+\lambda M_{1,0, k+1}(t)\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

Now,

$$
\begin{aligned}
M_{1,0, k}(t)= & \frac{1}{\bar{F}(t)} \int_{0}^{\infty} y \bar{F}^{k}(y+t) f(y+t) d y \\
= & \frac{1}{\left[1+\left(\frac{t}{\gamma}\right)^{c}\right]^{-\alpha}} \int_{0}^{\infty} y\left[1+\left(\frac{y+t}{\gamma}\right)^{c}\right]^{-k \alpha} \\
& \frac{c \alpha}{\gamma^{c}}(y+t)^{c-1}\left[1+\left(\frac{y+t}{\gamma}\right)^{c}\right]^{-\alpha-1} d y \\
= & \alpha\left[1+\left(\frac{t}{\gamma}\right)^{c}\right]^{\alpha}\left(\frac{\gamma \Gamma\left(\alpha(k+1)-\frac{1}{c}\right) \Gamma\left(\frac{1}{c}+1\right)}{\Gamma(\alpha(k+1)+1)}-\right. \\
& \left.\frac{t}{\alpha(k+1)}\right)
\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, the mean residual life function can be expressed as

$$
\begin{aligned}
\mu_{G}(t)= & e^{\lambda F(t)} \sum_{j=0}^{\infty} \sum_{k=0}^{j} a_{j, k}\left[M_{1,0, k}(t)+\lambda M_{1,0, k+1}(t)\right] \\
= & {\left[1+\left(\frac{t}{\gamma}\right)^{c}\right]^{\alpha} \Gamma\left(\frac{1}{c}+1\right) } \\
& \exp \left[\lambda\left(1-\left(1+\left(\frac{t}{\gamma}\right)^{c}\right)^{-\alpha}\right)\right] \\
& \sum_{j=0}^{\infty} \sum_{k=0}^{j} a_{j, k}\left[\alpha \gamma \frac{\Gamma\left(\alpha(k+1)-\frac{1}{c}\right)}{\Gamma(\alpha(k+1)+1)}+\right. \\
& \left.\lambda \alpha \gamma \frac{\Gamma\left(\alpha(k+2)-\frac{1}{c}\right)}{\Gamma(\alpha(k+2)+1)}-\frac{t}{k+1}-\frac{\lambda t}{k+2}\right]
\end{aligned}
$$

Remark 2 The CBurr distribution has four parameters and is flexible enough to analyze highly skewed and heavy-tailed datasets. As explained in the next subsection, estimating the parameters is not difficult. It can also be naturally extended for multivariate setup which is a great advantage of CBurr distribution in practical usage.

## B. Parameter Estimations: MLE

Let $y_{1}, y_{2}, \cdots, y_{n}$ denote a random sample of size $n$ from the new family of distributions characterized by the density function given in Eq. (15). The parameter vector $\Theta=\left(\lambda, \beta^{T}\right)^{T}$ represents the unknown parameters, where $\beta=(c, \alpha, \gamma)^{T}$ corresponds to the parameters of the baseline distribution. The
log-likelihood function for the parameter vector $\Theta$ can be expressed as follows:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\ell(\Theta)= & \sum_{i=1}^{n} \log \left[1+\lambda \bar{F}\left(y_{i}, \beta\right)\right]-\lambda \sum_{i=1}^{n} F\left(y_{i}, \beta\right)+\sum_{i=1}^{n} \log f\left(y_{i}, \beta\right) \\
= & n \log c \alpha-n \lambda+(c-1) \sum_{i=1}^{n} \log y_{i}-n c \log \gamma-n \lambda \\
= & (\alpha+1) \sum_{i=1}^{n} \log \left[1+\left(\frac{y_{i}}{\gamma}\right)^{c}\right]+ \\
& \sum_{i=1}^{n} \log \left[1+\frac{\lambda}{\left(1+\left(\frac{y_{i}}{\gamma}\right)^{c}\right)^{\alpha}}\right]+\lambda \sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(1+\left(\frac{y_{i}}{\gamma}\right)^{c}\right)^{-\alpha}
\end{aligned}
$$

By calculating the partial derivatives of the log-likelihood function with respect to $\lambda$ and $\beta$, we can derive the normal equations. Setting these derivatives to zero, we obtain:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \frac{\partial \ell}{\partial \lambda}=\sum_{i=1}^{n} \frac{\bar{F}\left(y_{i}, \beta\right)}{1+\lambda \bar{F}\left(y_{i}, \beta\right)}-\sum_{i=1}^{n} F\left(y_{i}, \beta\right) \text { and } \\
& \frac{\partial \ell}{\partial \beta}=\sum_{i=1}^{n} \frac{\lambda}{1+\lambda \bar{F}\left(y_{i}, \beta\right)} \frac{\partial \bar{F}\left(y_{i}, \beta\right)}{\partial \beta}-\lambda \sum_{i=1}^{n} \frac{\partial F\left(y_{i}, \beta\right)}{\partial \beta}+ \\
& \sum_{i=1}^{n} \frac{\partial \log f\left(y_{i}, \beta\right)}{\partial \beta}
\end{aligned}
$$

Upon equating the partial derivatives to zero, a system of equations is obtained. Solving this system simultaneously yields the maximum likelihood estimates (MLE) $\hat{\Theta}=$ $\left(\hat{\lambda}, \hat{\beta}^{T}\right)^{T}$ for $\Theta=\left(\lambda, \beta^{T}\right)^{T}$. Due to the absence of closedform solutions for these equations, numerical solutions obtained through iterative algorithms are required to solve them. The CBurr distribution exhibits different shapes due to the changing values of parameters, as depicted in Figs. 2 and 3.

Remark 3 These partial derivatives are set to zero and must be solved simultaneously to obtain the MLEs of the parameters of the CBurr model. As the closed-form solutions are not available, we have used an iterative method to solve these equations numerically. We have used the quasi-Newton Broyden Fletcher Goldfarb Shanno (BFGS) algorithm available in the R package 'optims' for solving the unconstrained nonlinear optimization problem. This helps in finding the MLE estimates of the CBurr model parameters.

## B. Evaluation Criteria

We use a variety of evaluation metrics to determine the goodness-of-fit for the proposed CBurr distribution for the degree distribution in a real-world complex network. Due to the fact that the actual distribution is discrete, we test the goodness-of-fit using the chi-square statistic. The chi-squared test is calculated by bootstrap rebalancing with 50 K synthetic datasets. We also calculate additional statistical measures, such as Root Mean Square Error (RMSE) and KL-Difference (KLD), as well as Mean Absolute Error (MAE), to further compare the goodness-of-fit of the proposed CBurr distribution model to other considered distributions.

## C. Analysis of results

The proposed CBurr and other distributions were implemented using R Software version 4.2.2 on a Windows desktop, equipped with an Intel Core i7-8700 CPU at 3.20 GHz , 6 GB of RAM, and a 64-bit operating system. These models can be easily run and simulated on a personal computer across various platforms. In Table I, we first provide the statistical properties of the different networks, including their node count, edge count, and descriptive statistics. In particular, the standard deviation (s), mean $(\mu)$, and coefficient of variation $(\mathrm{s} / \mu)$. It is interesting to note that the coefficient of variation for all these datasets is higher than 1 , indicating datasets have high variability. Table I also presents evidence of the proposed fitting using the Compounded Burr distribution for the node degree distribution in various networks. The parameters $(\gamma, \alpha, c, \lambda)$ of the Compounded Burr distribution were estimated numerically using the "optim" function with the L-BFGS-B algorithm in R software, initialized at $(\gamma, \alpha, c, \lambda)=(1,1,0.5,1.5)$. ## VI. DISCUSSIONS

In this article, we have introduced the compounded Burr (CBurr) distribution for modeling the node degree distribution of biological networks. The CBurr distribution is derived
from a family of continuous probability distributions, allowing for the inclusion of an additional parameter to enhance the flexibility and efficiency of the Burr XII distribution. Our data analysis and experiments have provided strong evidence supporting the superiority of the proposed CBurr distribution over traditional power law distributions. The CBurr distribution demonstrates better modeling capabilities, capturing the intricate connectivity patterns and characteristics observed in realworld biological networks. By incorporating the CBurr distribution, we are able to represent the entire node degree distribution accurately, considering both highly connected nodes (hubs) and nodes with lower degrees. This comprehensive modeling approach enables a more realistic representation of the network structure and facilitates a deeper understanding of biological systems. In future research, we will explore the applicability of the CBurr distribution in a broader range of network types and investigate its performance across various statistical properties.

In conclusion, the proposed CBurr distribution offers a valuable tool for the effective and efficient modeling of node degree distributions in biological networks. Its flexibility, accuracy, and ability to capture complex connectivity patterns make it a promising choice for analyzing and interpreting biological network data. By conducting extensive analyses of different network structures and characteristics, we aim to gain a deeper understanding of the versatility and robustness of the proposed distribution. We are confident that the CBurr distribution will continue to demonstrate its effectiveness and contribute to the modeling and analysis of diverse real-world networks.

abstract:
Complex biological networks, encompassing metabolic reactions, gene
interactions, and protein-protein interactions, often exhibit scale-free
characteristics with power-law degree distributions. However, empirical
evidence reveals significant deviations from ideal power-law fits,
necessitating more flexible and accurate modeling approaches. To address this
challenge, we introduce a novel Compounded Burr (CBurr) distribution, a novel
probability model derived from the Burr family, designed to capture the
intricate structural properties of biological networks. We rigorously establish
its statistical properties, including moment analysis, hazard functions, and
tail behavior, and provide a robust parameter estimation framework using the
maximum likelihood method. The CBurr distribution is broadly applicable to
networks with fat-tailed degree distributions, making it highly relevant for
modeling biological, social, and technological networks. To validate its
efficacy, we conduct an extensive empirical study on large-scale biological
network datasets, demonstrating that CBurr consistently outperforms
conventional power-law and alternative heavy-tailed models in fitting the
entire range of node degree distributions. Our proposed CBurr probability
distribution holds great promise for accurately capturing the complex nature of
biological networks and advancing our understanding of their underlying
mechanisms.
